					<description><![CDATA[As day one resulted in me planning and feeling like I knew exactly what to do, it is only fair that day 2 show me exactly what I should not have done. Â Here is a list of my first things I&#8217;ve learned not to do at VMworld. Do not schedule back to back sessions during [&#8230;]]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>As day one resulted in me planning and feeling like I knew exactly what to do, it is only fair that day 2 show me exactly what I should not have done. Â Here is a list of my first things I&#8217;ve learned not to do at VMworld.</p>
<ul>
<li>Do not schedule back to back sessions during lunch. Â The food is certainly better at 11.30am vs 1:45 pm.</li>
<li>Do not schedule sessions close together in time, but far apart in distance</li>
<li>Do not think you will have reliable Wi-Fi/LTE when there are 21,000 people using both of those on multiple devices.</li>
<li>Do not wear your &#8220;VMworld 2013&#8221; T-shirt that you got at registration to the first day of sessions. Â Come on now.</li>
<li>Don&#8217;t take pictures of slides during the presentations. Â You can download them later.</li>
</ul>
<p>Some of that is joking, some of that is serious.</p>
<p>Getting serious now: Â My first day of real sessions was probably too overbooked. Â I found myself distracted during current sessions trying to figure out how much time I had to make it to my next session. Â I should have left a bit more time in between to allow for things like snacks, walking, drinks, bathroom breaks, and other extra curriculars like the hangout space and hands-on labs. Â I will be adjusting my schedule accordingly, because I think I&#8217;m confident in saying that there is just as much to be gained from &#8220;unofficial&#8221; networking and experiences as there is from the actual sessions. Â Ultimately, cramming in as many sessions as possible is not necessarily the best way to do it.</p>
<p>Noted, VMworld. Â Tomorrow is another day!</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
