					<description><![CDATA[The 10th anniversary rendition of VMware&#8217;s flagship tech conference is officially under way! I&#8217;ve been a user and fan of VMware for about 8 years, thus making it a mega techie sin that this is only now my maiden voyage. Â I&#8217;ve never been lucky enough to make it out west for VMworld until now, and [&#8230;]]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>The 10th anniversary rendition of VMware&#8217;s flagship tech conference is officially under way!</p>
<p>I&#8217;ve been a user and fan of VMware for about 8 years, thus making it a mega techie sin that this is only now my maiden voyage. Â I&#8217;ve never been lucky enough to make it out west for VMworld until now, and being a VMworld rookie is already an interesting experience. There is SO much to do that the entire experience is extremely overwhelming, especially for a first timer.</p>
<ul>
<li>Hundreds of breakout sessions, hands on labs, and keynotes</li>
<li>Hundreds of presenters</li>
<li>Afterparties, meetups, tweetups, and vendor receptions</li>
<li>One of America&#8217;s coolest cities to explore</li>
</ul>
<p>My first strategy for making the most of VMworld was to concentrate on being a savvy traveler. Â I don&#8217;t travel much, so this is kind of a big deal for me. Â I got electronic boarding passes, I put my hotel, flight info, and VMworld agenda into a synced Evernote notebook, and finally I planned out routes to/from my hotel via both hotel shuttle and Frisco&#8217;s impressive public transit system (<a href="http://tripplanner.transit.511.org/">http://tripplanner.transit.511.org</a>Â is very helpful). Â This all worked out pretty well, leaving me with a smooth travel experience. Â It&#8217;s also really nice to Â have a couple of free/low cost methods of getting around this city. Â The first thing I did after checking into my hotel was to ride a cable car, which I found to be a really fun way to get around. Â The Powell Street cable car was especially impressive because it provided some spectacular views of the city. Â At Powell/California, for example, I could see all the way out to the bay bridge down a street luge&#8217;s dream of a hill. Â  All together, this planning and preparation left me feeling ready to hit the ground running when arriving in SFO.</p>
<p>My next strategy was to not worry too much about my sessions and labs. Â Sure, you want to get into some of these things that are relevant to your interests and career, but you have HUNDREDS to choose from. Â You could go over, over again, and still be making changes on your 5th time through schedule builder. Â Sign up for the ones that make sense and then don&#8217;t worry about it anymore. Â VMware makes them all available for download afterwards anyway. Â Ultimately I forced myself to stop making changes and focus on making the most of the ones I picked.</p>
<p>Day 1 for me was designed to be registration, check in, and getting my bearings in the city. Â It has been a success, and I&#8217;m looking forward to the rest of this experience.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
